  subhead="Your latest reel is a thirty-five-second time-lapse of a chimney rebuild on a Georgian townhouse in Walton Street — the camera mounted on the scaffold captures you dismantling the condemned upper courses brick by brick, stacking salvageable originals aside, then rebuilding in the Georgian stretcher bond with reclaimed handmade bricks bedded in NHL 5 lime mortar. The final frame zooms from the scaffold to reveal the completed stack — five courses of warm red brickwork, flush lime joints, a restored pargeted cornice detail, and three matching louvred pots on fresh haunching. Eight thousand views. A homeowner in Osney Island DMs: 'Your work is stunning. Our chimney is a Georgian terrace too — three pots, but the brickwork at the top looks awful. Mortar falling out, one pot has no haunching at all, and we can see daylight through a crack in the north side. Have been worried about it for two winters. About eight metres tall from the roof. Can you come and assess? Are we in danger of it collapsing?' You are at stack height on another job. Without AI DMs, the Osney message waits. With it, the AI asks whether any bricks or mortar have fallen, whether the public footpath passes beneath the chimney, and whether all three flues are active. She confirms: mortar has fallen into the gutter, the chimney overhangs the neighbour's garden, and two flues are active for gas boilers. Monday you call: Osney Island Georgian terrace, 3 pots, crumbling top courses, no haunching on one pot, daylight through north crack, 8 metres, mortar in gutter, overhangs neighbour, 2 active gas flues, 2-winter concern."
